{"questionId":"23653818","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Let&nbsp;<span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"f\\left( x \\right) = \\frac{1}{3}{x^3} + {x^2} - 15x + 17\">\n  <mi>f</mi>\n  <mrow>\n    <mo>(</mo>\n    <mi>x</mi>\n    <mo>)</mo>\n  </mrow>\n  <mo>=</mo>\n  <mfrac>\n    <mn>1</mn>\n    <mn>3</mn>\n  </mfrac>\n  <mrow>\n    <msup>\n      <mi>x</mi>\n      <mn>3</mn>\n    </msup>\n  </mrow>\n  <mo>+</mo>\n  <mrow>\n    <msup>\n      <mi>x</mi>\n      <mn>2</mn>\n    </msup>\n  </mrow>\n  <mo>−</mo>\n  <mn>15</mn>\n  <mi>x</mi>\n  <mo>+</mo>\n  <mn>17</mn>\n</math></span>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>The graph of <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"f\">\n  <mi>f</mi>\n</math></span> has horizontal tangents at the points where <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"x\">\n  <mi>x</mi>\n</math></span> = <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"a\">\n  <mi>a</mi>\n</math></span> and <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"x\">\n  <mi>x</mi>\n</math></span> = <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"b\">\n  <mi>b</mi>\n</math></span>, <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"a\">\n  <mi>a</mi>\n</math></span> &lt; <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"b\">\n  <mi>b</mi>\n</math></span>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Hence explain why the graph of <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"f\">\n  <mi>f</mi>\n</math></span> has a local maximum point at <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"x = a\">\n  <mi>x</mi>\n  <mo>=</mo>\n  <mi>a</mi>\n</math></span>.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p>first derivative changes from positive to negative at&nbsp; <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"x = a\">\n  <mi>x</mi>\n  <mo>=</mo>\n  <mi>a</mi>\n</math></span>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p>so local maximum at&nbsp;<span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"x = a\">\n  <mi>x</mi>\n  <mo>=</mo>\n  <mi>a</mi>\n</math></span>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>A</strong><strong>G</strong></em></p>\n<p><em><strong>[1 mark]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"23653818","referenceCode":"SPM.1.SL.TZ0.8c.ii","subjectId":"50-dp-mathematics-analysis-and-approaches","title":"Hence explain why the graph of f has a local maximum point at x = a .","paper":"1","level":"SL","questionNumber":"c.ii","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 1]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 5 —Calculus","Topic 5 —Calculus","SL 5.3—Differentiating polynomials, n E Z","Topic 5 —Calculus","SL 5.4—Tangents and normal","Topic 5 —Calculus","SL 5.8—Testing for max and min, optimisation. Points of inflexion"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}